ugi]]\n|birth_name      = Thomas Miller McClintock II\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1956|7|10}}\n|birth_place     = [[White Plains, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|party           = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse          = Lori McClintock\n|children        = 2\n|education       = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n'''Thomas Miller McClintock II''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|k|l|\u026a|n|t|\u0252|k}}; born July 10, 1956) is an American politician who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CA|4}}, serving since 2009. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He is a former [[California Assembly|Assemblyman]] and [[California State Senate|state Senator]]. McClintock unsuccessfully ran for [[Governor of California]] in the [[2003 California recall]] election and for [[Lieutenant Governor of California]] in the [[California lieutenant gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 California lieutenant gubernatorial election]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nMcClintock was born in [[White Plains, New York]]  and graduated in 1978 from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. Aged 23, he was elected [[Chairman]] of the [[Ventura County, California|Ventura County]] Republican Party, and served until 1981. He was chief of staff to State Senator [[Edward M. Davis|Ed Davis]] from 1980 to 1982. From 1992 to 1994, he served as the director of the Center for the California Taxpayer.<ref>[https://mcclintock.house.gov/about/full-biography Biography | Congressman Tom McClintock]. ''mcclintock.house.gov''. Retrieved on September 25, 2015.</ref> He was director of the [[Claremont Institute|Claremont Institute's Golden State Center for Policy Studies]] from 1995\u201396.<ref>[http://www.yologop.org/stay_informed/candidates/index.cfm/Tom_McClintock_7.htm \"Tom McClintock for Lt. Governor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210215301/http://www.yologop.org/stay_informed/candidates/index.cfm/Tom_McClintock_7.htm |date=2012-02-10 }} Retrieved on March 19, 2008</ref> McClintock is one of a handful of representatives that do not live in their own district; he resides in [[Elk Grove, California]], which is in [[California's 7th congressional district]].<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-congress-living-outside-district-20151222-html-htmlstory.html These California lawmakers don't live in the districts they represent]. ''latimes.com''. Retrieved on December 22nd, 2015.</ref>\n\n==California Assembly (1982\u20131992, 1996\u20132000)==\n\n===Elections===\nMcClintock ran for [[California's 36th State Assembly district]], based in [[Thousand Oaks, California|Thousand Oaks]], in 1982 at the age of 26 after redistricting. He defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Harriet Kosmo Henson 56\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=450790|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 1982|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 1984, he won re-election to a second term, defeating Tom Jolicoeur 72\u201328%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=444938|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 1984|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 1986, he won re-election to a third term, defeating Frank Nekimken 73\u201325%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=443080|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1986|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 1988, he won re-election to a fourth term, defeating George Webb II 70\u201329%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=441739|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1988|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 1990, he won re-election to a fifth term, defeating Ginny Connell 59\u201336%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=373460|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 1990|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter running for Congress in 1992 and for controller in 1994, he decided to run for the Assembly again in 1996. He ran for [[California's 38th State Assembly district]] and defeated Democrat Jon Lauritzen 56\u201340% to win his sixth assembly term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=368955|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 38 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1996|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 1998, McClintock won re-election to a seventh term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=280320|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Assembly 38 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1998|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nHe authored California's [[lethal injection]] use for [[Death penalty in California|California's death penalty law]]. He also opposed tax increases and supported spending cuts. He was a strong proponent of abolishing the car tax.<ref>[http://www.tommcclintock.com/meet-tom ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005210730/http://www.tommcclintock.com/meet-tom |date=October 5, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"nationaljournal.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/tom-mcclintock-ca/|title=Login|work=nationaljournal.com}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\n==California Senate (2000\u20132008)==\n[[File:Tom McClintock.jpg|thumb|Tom McClintock as a California State Senator]]\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2000, he decided to retire from the California Assembly to run for [[California's 19th State Senate district]]. He ranked first in the May 7th open primary with 52% of the vote. In November, he defeated Democrat Daniel Gonzalez 58\u201342%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=5772|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Senate 19 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2000|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 2004, he won re-election to a second term, defeating Paul Joseph Graber 61\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=71750|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA State Senate 19 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2004|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2008, McClintock voted against Proposition 2, which prohibits confining calves, pigs and hens in small cages in which they cannot extend their limbs. \"Farm animals are food, not friends\", he said in response to backlash to his no vote. He also cited concern about increased grocery bills.<ref name=\"McGreevy102108\">{{cite web|last1=McGreevy|first1=Patrick|title=Tom McClintock speaks out on farm animal, gay marriage measures|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2008/10/mcclintock----n.html|website=LA Times Blogs - L.A. NOW|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=21 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nMcClintock has a long history of opposing various tax increases. During the 2000 [[dot-com bubble]], he was instrumental in proposing a two-thirds reduction in the vehicle license fee, or [[car tax]]. In 2003, he opposed then-Governor [[Gray Davis]]'s attempt to rescind a rollback of a vehicle license fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/recall/20031001-9999_1n1tom.html|title=GOP's McClintock sticks to his guns even if it costs him|publisher=SignOnSanDiego.com|date=2003-10-01|first=Michael|last=Gardner}}</ref> McClintock has also opposed deficit reduction efforts that would have increased taxes. He supported the Bureaucracy Reduction and Closure Commission and [[performance-based budgeting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20040222/news_mz1e22state.html|title=Pressing measures|publisher=SignOnSanDiego.com|first=Robert M.|last=Stern|date=2004-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Statewide elections==\n\n===1994 Controller election===\n{{Main|California State Controller election, 1994}}\nHe ran for [[California State Controller]] after incumbent Democrat Gray Davis retired. He won the Republican primary, defeating John Morris, 61\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=113667|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA Controller \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 07, 1994|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In the general election, he faced [[Kathleen Connell]], former Special Assistant to [[Los Angeles Mayor]] [[Tom Bradley (American politician)|Tom Bradley]] and Director of [[Housing Authority of the City of Los Angeles|L.A. Housing Authority]]. Despite the fact that Connell outspent McClintock by a 3-to-1 margin, he only lost by two percentage points, 48\u201346%, with three other candidates receiving the other 6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=40634|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA Controller Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1994|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n===2002 Controller election===\n{{Main|California State Controller election, 2002}}\nMcClintock ran for State Controller again in 2002, facing Democratic nominee [[Steve Westly]], an [[eBay]] executive. Westly outspent him 5-to-1. McClintock's campaigns focused on increasing accountability for the state budget. The ads featured the character ''Angus McClintock'', a fictional cousin and fellow [[Scottish American]] extolling Tom McClintock's virtues of thriftiness and accountability with low-budget fifteen-second ads. He lost by a margin of just 0.2%, or 16,811 votes behind Westley, who won with a plurality of 45.3% of the vote. McClintock obtained 45.1% of the vote, while three other candidates obtained a combined 9.5% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=1608|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA Controller Race \u2013 Nov 05, 2002|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n===2003 recall gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|California gubernatorial recall election}}\nIn 2003, he ran for the recall election against incumbent Democrat Gray Davis. Republican and film actor [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] won the election with 49% of the vote. [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Lieutenant Governor of California|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Cruz Bustamante]] finished second with 31% of the vote, which was about 17 points behind Schwarzenegger. McClintock finished in third place with 14% of the vote, which was about 35 points behind Schwarzenegger. Together, Republicans Schwarzenegger and McClintock were supported by 5,363,778 Californians, or 62.1% of the vote. 132 other candidates obtained the remaining 6.4% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=6312|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA Governor Recall Race \u2013 Oct 07, 2003|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\nMcClintock performed the best in [[Stanislaus County, California|Stanislaus County]], where he obtained 24% of the vote. He also cracked 20% or higher in several other counties: [[Mariposa County, California|Mariposa]] (23%), [[Tuolumne County, California|Tuolumne]] (22%), [[Tehama County, California|Tehama]] (21%), [[Calaveras County, California|Calaveras]] (20%), [[Madera County, California|Madera]] (20%), [[Modoc County, California|Modoc]] (20%), [[Shasta County, California|Shasta]] (20%), [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]] (20%), and [[Ventura County, California|Ventura]] (20%).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20141021000759/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2003-special/gov.pdf ]</ref>\n\n===2006 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|California lieutenant gubernatorial election, 2006}}\nHe ran for [[Lieutenant Governor of California|lieutenant governor]] in the 2006 elections. He defeated Tony Farmer in the Republican primary, 94\u20136%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=112292|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA Lieutenant Governor \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 06, 2006|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In the general election, he lost to Democratic [[California Insurance Commissioner|State Insurance Commissioner]] [[John Garamendi]] 49\u201345%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=112362|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA  Lieutenant Governor Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1992\nAfter redistricting, State Assemblyman McClintock decided to retire in order to challenge Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Anthony C. Beilenson]] in [[California's 24th congressional district]]. He won the nine-candidate Republican primary with a plurality of 34% of the vote, beating second-place finisher Sang Korman by eleven percentage points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=514570|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA District 24 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 02, 1992|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> Beilenson defeated McClintock 56\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27539|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA District 24 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2008#District 4}}\nOn March 4, 2008, McClintock announced his candidacy for the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] in [[California's 4th congressional district]], which is hundreds of miles away from the district McClintock represented in the state Senate. The district's nine-term incumbent, fellow Republican [[John Doolittle]], decided to retire. McClintock was unable to vote for himself in either the primary or the general election because the [[California Constitution]] required him to maintain his legal residence in his State Senate district until the end of his Senate term. Furthermore, in order to vote using a ballot in regards to a specific congressional district, one must live within that district. Because Thousand Oaks is outside of California's Fourth Congressional District, McClintock was thus ineligible to vote for himself.<ref name=\"SacBee030408\"/>\n\nUpon McClintock's entry into the race, fellow Republicans [[Rico Oller]] and Eric Egland withdrew from the Republican primary and endorsed McClintock.<ref name=\"SacBee030408\">{{cite news|author=Hecht, Peter |title=McClintock in, Oller out in race to replace Doolittle |work=[[Sacramento Bee]] |date=2008-03-04 |url=http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/759440.html |accessdate=2008-03-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206125635/http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/759440.html |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Gunzberger, Ronecemb|title=California|work=Politics1.com|date=2008-03-05|url=http://www.politics1.com/blog-0308.htm#0305|accessdate=2008-03-05|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310221242/http://politics1.com/blog-0308.htm#0305|archivedate=2008-03-10|df=}}</ref> McClintock was endorsed by the [[Republican Liberty Caucus]],<ref>[http://www.rlc.org/2008/11/05/rlc-election-results/ \"RLC Election Results.\" Republican Liberty Caucus (November 5, 2008).] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212201341/http://www.rlc.org/2008/11/05/rlc-election-results/ |date=February 12, 2012 }}</ref> [[Club for Growth]], and U.S. Congressman [[Ron Paul]]. McClintock faced former U.S. Congressman [[Doug Ose]], a moderate represented the neighboring [[California's 3rd congressional district|3rd District]] from 1999 to 2005. Ose lived outside the district and was painted as a [[carpetbagger]] and a liberal who had voted to raise taxes and who voted for earmarks. McClintock defeated Ose 54\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=341896|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA District 04 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 03, 2008|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Democratic nominee was retired [[Usaf|Air Force]] [[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lt. Col.]] [[Charles Brown (California)|Charlie Brown]], who ran an unexpectedly strong race against Doolittle in 2006. In March 2008, Ose's campaign commercials criticized McClintock for receiving payments totaling over $300,000 in per diem living expenses during his time in the [[California State Senate]], despite the fact that he lived in [[Elk Grove, California|Elk Grove]], near Sacramento, for most of the year. McClintock maintained that the payments were justified because his legal residence was in Thousand Oaks, in his State Senate district. He stated, \"Every legislator's [Sacramento area] residence is close to the Capitol. My residential costs up here are much greater than the average legislator because my family is here.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-mcclintock23mar23,0,6751476.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Patrick|last=McGreevy|title=McClintock criticized for taking per diem housing allowance|date=March 23, 2008}}</ref> However, Ose's campaign commercials argued McClintock does not own or rent a home in the 19th district, but uses his mother's address. These attacks prompted a response from McClintock's wife, Lori, who said McClintock stays with his mother in order to better care for her after she fell ill and after the death of her husband.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/963198.html|title=Ballot Watch: \"Ose's attack on McClintock for taking per diem riles rival's wife\"|work=[[Sacramento Bee]]|date=May 24, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206125641/http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/963198.html|archivedate=December 6, 2008|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> McClintock ran ads attacking Brown's participation at a 2005 protest by [[Code Pink]], an infamous [[anti-war]] group, and argued Brown supported [[Gay marriage in California|gay marriage]] but not the troops in Iraq. He also portrayed Brown as a clone of [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]].<ref name=\"nationaljournal.com\"/>\n\nBy November 23, 2008, McClintock led Brown by 1,566 votes (0.4% of the vote), 184,190 to 182,624. Subsequent returns expanded the margin slightly with the last returns coming in from [[El Dorado County]] shortly after [[Thanksgiving]]. On December 1, 2008, McClintock declared victory and on December 3, 2008, Brown conceded the race. McClintock defeated Brown by a margin of 0.5%, or 1,800 votes.<ref>{{cite book |title=2014 Almanac of American Politics |last2=Barone |first2=Chuck |last1=McCutcheon|first1=Michael |publisher=The University of Chicago Press |year= 2013}}</ref> He prevailed by a 3,500-vote margin in [[Placer County]], the largest county in the district. Brown won just three of the district's nine counties: Sierra (49.8%), Plumas (47.9%), and Nevada (42.3%).<ref>[http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/23_34_us_reps.pdf \"United States Representative (final results)\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221042514/http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008_general/23_34_us_reps.pdf |date=December 21, 2008 }} Office of the California Secretary of State, Retrieved on December 26, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theunion.com/article/20081122/NEWS/811220440/1066&ParentProfile=1053&title=McClintock%20declares%20victory |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524102543/http://www.theunion.com/article/20081122/NEWS/811220440/1066%26ParentProfile%3D1053%26title%3DMcClintock%20declares%20victory |archive-date=May 24, 2011 |title=McClintock declares victory |work=The Union |date=November 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 7, 2017 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Ultimately, McClintock won mainly on the strength of coattails from [[John McCain]], who carried the 4th with 54 percent of the vote, his fifth-best total in the state.\n\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2010#District 4}}\nMcClintock was challenged in the Republican primary again, this time by Michael Babich. He easily defeated Babich 78\u201322%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=641309|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA District 04 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 08, 2010|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> On November 2, he easily won re-election to a second term, defeating businessman [[Clint Curtis]] 61\u201331%, winning all of the counties in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=539273|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA \u2013 District 04 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 4}}\nRedistricting pushed the 4th well to the south. It now stretched from the Sacramento suburbs to the outer suburbs of [[Fresno]]. Only three counties remained from the old 4th: Nevada, Placer, and El Dorado. However, it is as strongly Republican as its predecessor.\n\nHe easily won re-election to a third term, defeating Democrat [[Jack Uppal]] 61\u201339%. He won all but two of the district's ten counties: Nevada (37%) and Alpine (41%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=768433|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 CA \u2013 District 04 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012|work=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2014#District 4}}\nMcClintock won re-election, finishing first in California's \"top two\" primary, and defeating moderate Republican challenger, National Guard Major Art Moore in the general election, 60\u201340%.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/us/politics/mcclintock-faces-bid-from-moderate-art-moore.html A Rare G.O.P. Battle Forces an Incumbent to Look Left], [[New York Times]], Norimitsu Onishi, April 20, 2014. Retrieved on October 6, 2015.</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2016}}\nMcClintock again finished first in the primary and subsequently defeated Democrat Robert W. Derlet, a physician, environmentalist and retired [[University of California, Davis|UC Davis]] professor, in the general election, 63\u201337%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article61789327.html|title=Bob Derlet, doctor and environmentalist, challenging Rep. Tom McClintock|work=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=February 22, 2016|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California%27s_4th_Congressional_District_election,_2016|title=California's 4th Congressional District election, 2016\n|work=[[Ballotpedia]]|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring the [[112th Congress]] McClintock was one of 40 \"staunch\" members of the [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> who frequently voted against Republican party leadership and vocally expressed displeasure with House bills.<ref name=rsc>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/17/us/politics/house-freshmen-not-as-defiant-as-their-reputation-suggests.html?_r=1&hp|title=G.O.P. Freshmen Not as Defiant as Reputation Suggests|first=Jennifer|last=Steinhauer|publisher=New York Times|date=2012-03-16}}</ref> In 2011, McClintock voted against the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] as part of a controversial provision that allows the government and the military to indefinitely detain American citizens and others without trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/ndaa-bill-how-did-your-congress-member-vote-384362?page=1|title=NDAA Bill: How Did Your Congress Member Vote?|date=16 December 2011|work=International Business Times}}</ref> McClintock's Chief of Staff, Igor Birman, was a candidate for Congress in [[California's 7th congressional district]] in 2014.\n\nIn 2009, McClintock signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any [[global warming]] legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mcclintock.pdf |format=PDF |title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Tom McClintock |publisher=Americansforprosperity.org |accessdate=2015-03-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219061216/http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax/ |archivedate=2015-02-19 |df= }}</ref>\n\nMcClintock voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> He voted against the first version of the bill, displeased with the removal of deductions related to medical expenses, student loan interest and [[casualty loss]]. Those three items were addressed in the final version of the bill which McClintock voted 'yay'. McClintock claims the bill will \"restore American workers to an internationally competitive position.\" He has expressed concern regarding the bill's impact on the [[budget deficit]] and anticipates that it will be addressed \"by spending reforms this coming year.\"<ref name=\"Bee122117\">{{cite web|title=Why Tom McClintock changed his tax vote|url=http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article191126269.html|website=The Sacramento Bee|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 McClintock voted against the repeal of Obamacare budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcclintock.house.gov/newsroom/vote-notes/hr-1892-bipartisan-budget-act-of-2018-no/|title=H.R. 1892 - Bipartisan Budget Act of 2018: NO|date=9 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Tom McClintock called for special prosecutor Mueller against President Trump. McClintock felt that the firing of Comey justified the special prosecutor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-republican-tom-mcclintock-calls-for-1494519776-htmlstory.html|title=Republican Rep. Tom McClintock calls for independent prosecutor to take over FBI's Russia investigation|first=Sarah D.|last=Wire|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nMcClintock supported the [[Water Rights Protection Act]], a bill that would prevent federal agencies from requiring certain entities to relinquish their water rights to the United States in order to use [[public lands]].<ref name=3189cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3189 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44956|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> The bill was a reaction to the [[United States Forest Service]]'s decision to pursue a \"new regulation to demand that water rights be transferred to the federal government as a condition for obtaining permits needed to operate 121 ski resorts that cross over federal lands.\"<ref name=COtiptonbill>{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=Audrey|title=Tipton Bill Seeks to Stop Feds from Trampling Water Rights|url=http://thecoloradoobserver.com/2013/10/tipton-bill-seeks-to-stop-feds-from-trampling-water-rights/|accessdate=12 March 2014|newspaper=The Colorado Observer|date=11 October 2013}}</ref> McClintock supported the bill, saying that the Forest Service's regulation \"illustrates an increasingly hostile attitude by this agency toward those who make productive use of our vast national forests, in this case by enhancing and attracting the tourism upon which our mountain communities depend.\"<ref name=\"COtiptonbill\"/>\n\nFor his five terms in office, McClintock was the primary sponsor of three bills that were enacted into law.  On June 14, 2013, McClintock introduced the bill [[To authorize the Secretary of the Interior to take certain Federal lands located in El Dorado County, California, into trust for the benefit of the Shingle Springs Band of Miwok Indians (H.R. 2388; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would take specified federal land in [[El Dorado County, California]], into trust for the [[Shingle Springs Band of Miwok Indians]].<ref name=2388sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2388 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/2388|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>  The other two bills were to rename Post Offices.  (H.R. 3892 and H.R. 3319).<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/tom_mcclintock/412295 GovTrack Rep. Tom McClintock]. ''govtrack.us''. Retrieved on October 29, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs|Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Federal Lands|Subcommittee on Federal Lands]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]\n* [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n* [[American Sikh Congressional Caucus]]\n* [[Liberty Caucus]]\n*[[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== Animal rights ===\n\nMcClintock has said that \"farm animals are food, not friends.\"<ref name=\"McGreevy102108\"/> He supports [[Sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] of wild horses for population control.<ref name=\"Swerdloff91416\">{{cite web|last1=Swerdloff|first1=Alex|title=The Controversial Plan to Kill 45,000 Wild Horses to Make Room for Cattle Farming|url=https://munchies.vice.com/en_us/article/kbk37x/americas-wild-horses-could-be-euthanized-to-make-room-for-livestock|website=Munchies|publisher=Vice|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\n\nMcClintock opposes [[same-sex marriage]] and in 2008, stated \"calling a homosexual partnership a marriage doesn\u2019t make it one.\"<ref name=\"McGreevy102108\"/>\n\n=== Marijuana ===\n\nTom McClintock endorsed Proposition 64 to legalize marijuana. Tom McClintock legislated bills to federally legalize marijuana.\n\nMcClintock - Amendment Bill to HR 2578 and McClintock/Polis (HR 2578) are to stop federal interference with state marijuana. It prohibits the Department of Justice from spending any federal funds to prosecute marijuana offenders. It was voted down in 2015 by over 80% of House Republicans.  The McClintock bill is a rider to the budget appropriations bill. McClintock's marijuana bill was voted down again in March 2018.<ref name=\"ODD\">{{cite web|title=H.Amdt. 334 (McClintock) to H.R. 2578: Amendment sought to prohibit the use of funds by various states to prevent any of them from implementing their own laws that authorize the use, distribution, possessions, or cultivation of marijuana on non-Federal land|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/114-2015/h285|website=odd.org|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate Change ===\n\nMcClintock does not believe climate change is caused by humans.  He has said: \"You see, it was me \u2013 and not Al Gore \u2013 who discovered the theory of Global Climate Change, and yet all you ever hear is Al Gore said this and Al Gore said that. My climate change discovery came in the fall of 1964, when Miss Conroy took our third grade class to the Museum of Natural History. It was there that we saw the panorama of dinosaurs tromping around the steamy swamps that are now part of Wyoming.  That panorama was right next to the exhibit of the Wooly Mammoths foraging on glaciers that were also once the same part of Wyoming.  And I thought to myself, 'Gee, those dinosaurs are nifty.\u201d  And then I thought to myself, \u201cGood God, the climate must have changed from time to time.'\" <ref name=\"Inconvenient Questions\">{{cite web|title=Inconvenient Questions|url=https://mcclintock.house.gov/newsroom/speeches/inconvenient-questions|website=mcclintock.house.gov|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change|title=California State Assembly District 36 election, 1982<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=450790 Our Campaigns] \"California State Assembly 36 Race \u2013 November 2, 1982,\" (Retrieved on August 1, 2009).</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n|party=Republican Party (United States)\n|candidate=Tom McClintock\n|votes=60,702\n|percentage=55.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change||party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Harriet Kosmo Henson|votes=47,932|percentage=44.1}}\n{{Election box total no change||votes=108,634|percentage=100}}\n{{Election box turnout no change||percentage=}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing||winner=Republican Party (United States)|loser=Democratic Par